Hadley Wickham and Garret Grolemund say in their book [R for Data Science](http://r4ds.had.co.nz) that *`summarise()` is not
terribly useful unless we pair it with `group_by()`. This changes the unit of analysis from the complete dataset to individual
groups.*

This one sentence (and the reasons comming below) let me understand a major truth in data transformation with dplyr : *`summarise()` 
and `group_by()` once combined are terribly useful.*

Why once combined these two verbs are so powerful ? Because they provide one of the tools that you’ll use most commonly 
when working with dplyr (that is to say when you are doing data transformation in the 21^{st} century): grouped summaries.

What is grouped summaries ? Why it is so important ? And what it looks like ?

# Grouped summaries 

Grouped summaries are your statistics summarize using a function of your choice by any groups you want. Knowing that this meaning is 
only understood by me, let us give a simplified look at group summaries. 
